# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: detonation-velocity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] Brisance is of practical importance in explosives engineering for determining the effectiveness of an explosion in blasting and quarrying, and in weaponry such as fragmenting shells, bomb casings, grenades, and plastic explosives.
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] The sand crush test and Trauzl lead block test are commonly used to determine the relative brisance in comparison to TNT (which is considered a standard reference for many purposes).
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] The value of brisance depends on the application.
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] At one extreme, if an explosive is to be used for propulsion, e.g. by driving a piston or a bullet, brisance is likely to be undesirable, because the objective will be to *move* the load, not to shatter it or the engine or firearm, nor to produce a loud report.
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] Such propulsive charges are designed to burn controllably, such as carburetted fuel/air mixes in vehicle piston engines, or nitrocellulose fibres or grains of controlled textures in firearm cartridges.
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] For certain types of blasting, as in some civil engineering works, the objective is to loosen the undesired material with the least amount of explosion and expense, both in explosive and safety precautions.
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] Similarly, in quarrying a product such as slate, in which the objective is to loosen it from surrounding rock with as little damage as possible, no more brisance than is necessary to split off the valuable product profitably, without unacceptable waste, is desired.
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] For this purpose blasting powder of *low* brisance is necessary.
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] In shattering hard rock or military defences, high brisance generally is necessary, so high explosives with extremely high detonation velocity are used as far as is practical.
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] One of the most brisant of the conventional explosives is cyclotrimethylene trinitramine (also known as RDX or Hexogen).
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] RDX is the explosive agent in the plastic explosive commonly known as C-4, constituting 91% RDX by mass.
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] Fragmentation occurs by the action of the transmitted shock wave, the strength of which depends on the detonation pressure of the explosive.
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] Generally, the higher this pressure, the finer the fragments generated.
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] High detonation pressure correlates with high detonation velocity, the speed at which the detonation wave propagates through the explosive, but not necessarily with the explosive's total energy (or work capacity), some of which may be released after passage of the detonation wave.
[src:detonation-velocity/brisance] A more brisant explosive, therefore, projects smaller fragments but not necessarily at a higher velocity than a less brisant one.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] In chemistry, the **burn rate** (or burning rate) is a measure of the linear combustion rate of a compound or substance such as a candle or a solid propellant.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] It is measured in length over time, such as millimeters per second or inches per second.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] Among the variables affecting burn rate are pressure and temperature.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] Burn rate is an important parameter, especially in propellants, because it determines the rate at which exhaust gases are generated from the burning propellant, which decides the flow rate through the nozzle.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] The thrust generated in the rocket of a missile depends on this flow rate.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] Thus, knowing the burn rate of a propellant and how it changes under various conditions is of fundamental importance in the successful design of a solid rocket motor.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] The concept of burn rate is also relevant in case of liquid propellants.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] One device for measuring the burning rate is a V-shaped metal channel about 1–2 feet long wherein a sample is placed, with a cross-sectional dimension of approximately 6 mm or 1/4 in.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] The sample is ignited on one end, and time is measured until the flame front reaches the other.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] Burn rate (typically expressed in mm/s or in/s) is the sample length over time at a given pressure and temperature.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] For solid fuel propellant, the most common method of measuring burn rate is the Crawford Type Strand Burning Rate Bomb System (also known as the Crawford Burner or Strand Burner), as described in MIL-STD-286C.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] A substance is characterized by a burn rate vs. pressure chart and burn rate vs temperature chart.
[src:detonation-velocity/burn-rate-chemistry] However, there is a difference in opinion in differentiating the three in the absence of firm numbers at a given pressure or temperature.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] The **Chapman–Jouguet condition** holds approximately in detonation waves in high explosives.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] It states that the detonation propagates at a velocity at which the reacting gases just reach sonic velocity (in the frame of the leading shock wave) as the reaction ceases.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] David Chapman and Émile Jouguet originally (c.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] 1900) stated the condition for an infinitesimally thin detonation.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] A physical interpretation of the condition is usually based on the later modelling (c.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] 1943) by Yakov Borisovich Zel'dovich, John von Neumann, and Werner Döring (the so-called ZND detonation model).
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] In more detail (in the ZND model) in the frame of the leading shock of the detonation wave, gases enter at supersonic velocity and are compressed through the shock to a high-density, subsonic flow.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] This sudden change in pressure initiates the chemical (or sometimes, as in steam explosions, physical) energy release.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] The energy release re-accelerates the flow back to the local speed of sound.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] It can be shown fairly simply, from the one-dimensional gas equations for steady flow, that the reaction must cease at the sonic ("CJ") plane, or there would be discontinuously large pressure gradients at that point.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] The sonic plane forms a so-called choke point that enables the lead shock, and reaction zone, to travel at a constant velocity, undisturbed by the expansion of gases in the rarefaction region beyond the CJ plane.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] This simple one-dimensional model is quite successful in explaining detonations.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] However, observations of the structure of real chemical detonations show a complex three-dimensional structure, with parts of the wave traveling faster than average, and others slower.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] Indeed, such waves are quenched as their structure is destroyed.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] The Wood–Kirkwood detonation theory can correct for some of these limitations.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] Here the subscript 1 and 2 identifies flow properties (pressure p , density $\rho$ ) upstream and downstream of the wave and m is the constant mass flux and q is the heat released in the wave.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] where M is the Mach number and c is the speed of sound, in other words, downstream flow is sonic with respect to the Chapman-Jouguet wave.
[src:detonation-velocity/chapman-jouguet-condition] The upper sign applies for the **Upper Chapman-Jouguet** point (detonation) and the lower sign applies for the **Lower Chapman-Jouguet** point (deflagration).
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] Deflagrations are often used in engineering applications when the force of the expanding gas is used to move an object such as a projectile down a barrel, or a piston in an internal combustion engine.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] Deflagration systems and products can also be used in mining, demolition and stone quarrying via gas pressure blasting as a beneficial alternative to high explosives.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] When studying or discussing explosive safety, or the safety of systems containing explosives, the terms deflagration, detonation and deflagration-to-detonation transition (commonly referred to as DDT) must be understood and used appropriately to convey relevant information.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] As explained above, a deflagration is a subsonic reaction, whereas a detonation is a supersonic (greater than the sound speed of the material) reaction.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] Distinguishing between a deflagration or a detonation can be difficult to impossible to the casual observer.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] Rather, confidently differentiating between the two requires instrumentation and diagnostics to ascertain reaction speed in the affected material.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] Therefore, when an unexpected event or an accident occurs with an explosive material or an explosive-containing system, it is usually impossible to know whether the explosive deflagrated or detonated as both can appear as very violent, energetic reactions.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] Therefore, the energetic materials community coined the term "high explosive violent reaction" or "HEVR" to describe a violent reaction that, because it lacked diagnostics to measure sound-speed, could have been either a deflagration or a detonation.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] The underlying flame physics can be understood with the help of an idealized model consisting of a uniform one-dimensional tube of unburnt and burned gaseous fuel, separated by a thin transitional region of width $\delta \;$ in which the burning occurs.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] The burning region is commonly referred to as the flame or flame front.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] In equilibrium, thermal diffusion across the flame front is balanced by the heat supplied by burning.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] Two characteristic timescales are important here.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] where $\kappa \;$ is the thermal diffusivity.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] where $\Delta U\;$ is the activation barrier for the burning reaction and $T_{f}\;$ is the temperature developed as the result of burning; the value of this so-called "flame temperature" can be determined from the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] For a stationary moving (unclear) deflagration front, these two timescales must be equal: the heat generated by burning is equal to the heat carried away by heat transfer.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] This simplified model neglects the change of temperature and thus the burning rate across the deflagration front.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] This model also neglects the possible influence of turbulence.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] As a result, this derivation gives only the laminar flame speed—hence the designation $S_{l}\;$ .
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] Damage to buildings, equipment and people can result from a large-scale, short-duration deflagration.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] The potential damage is primarily a function of the total amount of fuel burned in the event (total energy available), the maximum reaction velocity that is achieved, and the manner in which the expansion of the combustion gases is contained.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] Vented deflagrations tend to be less violent or damaging than contained deflagrations.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] In free-air deflagrations, there is a continuous variation in deflagration effects relative to the maximum flame velocity.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] When flame velocities are low, the effect of a deflagration is to release heat, such as in a flash fire.
[src:detonation-velocity/deflagration] At flame velocities near the speed of sound, the energy released is in the form of pressure, and the resulting high pressure can damage equipment and buildings.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] "Cordtex" and "Primacord" are two of many trademarks which have slipped into use as a generic term for this material.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] As a transmission medium, it can act as a downline between the initiator (usually a trigger) and the blast area, and as a trunkline connecting several different explosive charges.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] As a timing mechanism, detonation cord detonates at a very reliable rate (about 6,000–7,000 m/s or 23,000–26,000 ft/s), enabling engineers to control the pattern in which charges are detonated.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] This is particularly useful for demolitions, when structural elements need to be destroyed in a specific order to control the collapse of a building.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] While it looks like nylon cord, the core is a compressed powdered explosive, usually PETN (pentrite), and it is initiated by the use of a blasting cap.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] Detonation cord will initiate most commercial high explosives (dynamite, gelignite, sensitised gels, etc.) but will not initiate less sensitive blasting agents like ANFO on its own.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] 25 to 50 grain/foot (5.3 to 10.6 g/m) detonation cord has approximately the same initiating power as a #8 blasting cap in every 2 to 4 inches (5 to 10 cm) along its entire length.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] A small charge of PETN, TNT, or other explosive booster is required to bridge between the cord and a charge of insensitive blasting agent like ANFO or most water gels.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] Detonating cord is rated in explosive mass per unit length.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] This is expressed in grains per foot in the United States, or in grams per metre elsewhere.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] A "grams per metre" rating will be roughly one fifth the "grains per foot" rating.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] For example, "50 grain det. cord" refers to detonating cord which has 50 grains of explosive per foot of length—or approximately 10 g/m.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] Low-yield detonating cord can be used as a precision cutting charge to remove cables, pipes, wiring, fiber optics, and other utility bundles by placing one or more complete wraps around the target.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] Detonation cord is used in commercial boilers to break up clinkers (solidified coal ash slag) adhering to tube structures.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] Also a vertical centered cord being lowered into the water of a drilled well can remove any clogging that obstructs water flow.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] Higher-yield detonating cord can be used to cut down small trees, although the process is very uneconomical compared to using bulk explosive, or even a chainsaw.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] High-yield detonating cord placed by divers has been used to remove old dock pilings and other underwater obstructions.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] Creating a slipknot from detonating cord yields a field-improvised device that can be quickly employed to cut a locked doorknob off a door.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] Detonation cord can be taped in several rings to the outline of a military man-sized target and detonated, breaching a man-sized hole into wooden doors or light interior walls.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] Detonating cord is also employed directly in building demolition where thin concrete slabs need be broken via channels drilled parallel to the surface, an advantage over dynamite since a lower minimum of explosive force may be used and smaller diameter holes are sufficient to contain the explosive.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] Anything much more substantial than these uses requires the use of additional explosives.
[src:detonation-velocity/detcord] In Filipino, the corresponding word *mitsa* has come to be used in the phrase *mitsa ng buhay*, which translates to "detonating cord of [one's] life", a metaphor for something that is very likely to cause one's death via direct jeopardy (e.g. extreme sports, versus smoking).
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] If the explosive is confined before detonation, such as in an artillery shell, the force produced is focused on a much smaller area, and the pressure is significantly intensified.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] This results in an explosive velocity that is higher than if the explosive had been detonated in open air.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] Unconfined velocities are often approximately 70 to 80 percent of confined velocities.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] Explosive velocity is increased with smaller particle size (i.e., increased spatial density), increased charge diameter, and increased confinement (i.e., higher pressure).
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] Typical detonation velocities for organic dust mixtures range from 1,400 to 1,650 m/s.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] Gas explosions can either deflagrate or detonate based on confinement; detonation velocities are generally around 1,700 m/s but can be as high as 3,000 m/s.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] Solid explosives often have detonation velocities ranging beyond 4,000 m/s to 10,300 m/s.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] Detonation velocity can be measured by the Dautriche method.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] In essence, this method relies on the time lag between the initiation of two ends of a detonating fuse of a known detonation velocity, inserted radially at two points into the explosive charge at a known distance apart.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] When the explosive charge is detonated, it triggers one end of the fuse, then the second end.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] This causes two detonation fronts travelling in opposite direction along the length of the detonating fuse, which meet at a specific point away from the centre of the fuse.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] Knowing the distance along the detonation charge between the two ends of the fuse, the position of the collision of the detonation fronts, and the detonation velocity of the detonating fuse, the detonation velocity of the explosive is calculated and is expressed in km/s.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] In other words "VOD is the velocity or rate of propagation of chemical decomposition/reaction." And for high explosives, it is generally above 1,000 m/s.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] In the cases where a material has not received dedicated testing, rough predictions based upon gas behavior theory are sometimes used (see Chapman–Jouguet condition).
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation-velocity] The detonation velocity can be effectively determined by the Chapman–Jouguet (CJ) state, which represents the minimum sustainable steady detonation speed.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Detonations occur in both conventional solid and liquid explosives, as well as in reactive gases.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] TNT, dynamite, and C4 are examples of high power explosives that detonate.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] The velocity of detonation in solid and liquid explosives is much higher than that in gaseous ones, which allows the wave system to be observed with greater detail (higher resolution).
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] A very wide variety of fuels may occur as gases (e.g. hydrogen), droplet fogs, or dust suspensions.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] In addition to dioxygen, oxidants can include halogen compounds, ozone, hydrogen peroxide, and oxides of nitrogen.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Gaseous detonations are often associated with a mixture of fuel and oxidant in a composition somewhat below conventional flammability ratios.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] They happen most often in confined systems, but they sometimes occur in large vapor clouds.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Other materials, such as acetylene, ozone, and hydrogen peroxide, are detonable in the absence of an oxidant (or reductant).
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] In these cases the energy released results from the rearrangement of the molecular constituents of the material.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Detonation was discovered in 1881 by four French scientists Marcellin Berthelot and Paul Marie Eugène Vieille and Ernest-François Mallard and Henry Louis Le Chatelier.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] The mathematical predictions of propagation were carried out first by David Chapman in 1899 and by Émile Jouguet in 1905, 1906 and 1917.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] The next advance in understanding detonation was made by John von Neumann and Werner Döring in the early 1940s and Yakov B.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Zel'dovich and Aleksandr Solomonovich Kompaneets in the 1960s.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] The simplest theory to predict the behaviour of detonations in gases is known as the Chapman–Jouguet (CJ) condition, developed around the turn of the 20th century.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] This theory, described by a relatively simple set of algebraic equations, models the detonation as a propagating shock wave accompanied by exothermic heat release.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Such a theory describes the chemistry and diffusive transport processes as occurring abruptly as the shock passes.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] A more complex theory was advanced during World War II independently by Zel'dovich, von Neumann, and Döring.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] This theory, now known as ZND theory, admits finite-rate chemical reactions and thus describes a detonation as an infinitesimally thin shock wave, followed by a zone of exothermic chemical reaction.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] With a reference frame of a stationary shock, the following flow is subsonic, so that an acoustic reaction zone follows immediately behind the lead front, the Chapman–Jouguet condition.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] There is also some evidence that the reaction zone is semi-metallic in some explosives.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Both theories describe one-dimensional and steady wavefronts.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] However, in the 1960s, experiments revealed that gas-phase detonations were most often characterized by unsteady, three-dimensional structures, which can only, in an averaged sense, be predicted by one-dimensional steady theories.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] The Wood-Kirkwood detonation theory can correct some of these limitations.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Experimental studies have revealed some of the conditions needed for the propagation of such fronts.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] In confinement, the range of composition of mixes of fuel and oxidant and self-decomposing substances with inerts are slightly below the flammability limits and, for spherically expanding fronts, well below them.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] The influence of increasing the concentration of diluent on expanding individual detonation cells has been elegantly demonstrated.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Similarly, their size grows as the initial pressure falls.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Since cell widths must be matched with minimum dimension of containment, any wave overdriven by the initiator will be quenched.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Mathematical modeling has steadily advanced to predicting the complex flow fields behind shocks inducing reactions.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] To date, none has adequately described how the structure is formed and sustained behind unconfined waves.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] When used in explosive devices, the main cause of damage from a detonation is the supersonic blast front (a powerful shock wave) in the surrounding area.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] This is a significant distinction from deflagrations where the exothermic wave is subsonic and maximum pressures for non-metal specks of dust are approximately 7–10 times atmospheric pressure.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Therefore, detonation is a feature for destructive purposes while deflagration is favored for the acceleration of firearms' projectiles.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] However, detonation waves may also be used for less destructive purposes, including deposition of coatings to a surface or cleaning of equipment (e.g. slag removal) and even explosively welding together metals that would otherwise fail to fuse.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Pulse detonation engines use the detonation wave for aerospace propulsion.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] The first flight of an aircraft powered by a pulse detonation engine took place at the Mojave Air & Space Port on January 31, 2008.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Unintentional detonation when deflagration is desired is a problem in some devices.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] In Otto cycle, or gasoline engines it is called engine knocking or pinging, and it causes a loss of power.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] It can also cause excessive heating, and harsh mechanical shock that can result in eventual engine failure.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] In firearms, it may cause catastrophic and potentially lethal failure.
[src:detonation-velocity/detonation] Pulse detonation engines are a form of pulsed jet engine that has been experimented with on several occasions as this offers the potential for good fuel efficiency.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] A **dust explosion** is the rapid combustion of fine particles suspended in the air within an enclosed location.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Dust explosions can occur where any dispersed powdered combustible material is present in high-enough concentrations in the atmosphere or other oxidizing gaseous medium, such as pure oxygen.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Dust explosions are a frequent hazard in coal mines, grain elevators and silos, and other industrial environments.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] They are also commonly used by special effects artists, filmmakers, and pyrotechnicians, given their spectacular appearance and ability to be safely contained under certain carefully controlled conditions.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Thermobaric weapons exploit this principle by rapidly saturating an area with an easily combustible material and then igniting it to produce explosive force.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] These weapons are the most powerful non-nuclear explosives in existence.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] If rapid combustion occurs in a confined space, enormous overpressures can build up, causing major structural damage and flying debris.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] The sudden release of energy from a "detonation" can produce a shockwave, either in open air or in a confined space.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] If the spread of flame is at subsonic speed, the phenomenon is sometimes called a "deflagration", although looser usage calls both phenomena "explosions".
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Dust explosions may be classified as being either "primary" or "secondary" in nature.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Primary dust explosions may occur inside process equipment or similar enclosures, and are generally controlled by pressure relief through purpose-built ducting to the external atmosphere.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Secondary dust explosions are the result of dust accumulation inside a building being disturbed and ignited by the primary explosion, resulting in a much more dangerous uncontrolled explosion that can affect the entire structure.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Historically, fatalities from dust explosions have largely been the result of secondary dust explosions.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Many common materials which are known to burn can generate a dust explosion, such as coal dust and sawdust.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] In addition, many otherwise mundane organic materials can also be dispersed into a dangerous dust cloud, such as grain, flour, starch, sugar, powdered milk, cocoa, coffee, and pollen.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Powdered metals (such as aluminum, magnesium, and titanium) can form explosive suspensions in air, if finely divided.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] A gigantic explosion of flour dust destroyed a mill in Minnesota on May 2, 1878, killing 14 workers at the Washburn A Mill and another four in adjacent buildings.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] A similar problem occurs in sawmills and other places dedicated to woodworking.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] For example, in machining operations downstream of the AM build, excess powder liberated from porosities in the support structures can be exposed to sparks from the cutting interface.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Efforts are underway not only to build this knowledgebase within the industry but also to share it with local fire departments, who do periodic fire-safety inspections of businesses in their districts and who can expect to answer alarms at shops or plants where AM is now part of the production mix.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Although not strictly a dust, paper particles emitted during processing – especially rolling, unrolling, calendaring/slitting, and sheet-cutting – are also known to pose an explosion hazard.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Enclosed paper mill areas subject to such dangers commonly maintain very high air humidities to reduce the chance of airborne paper dust explosions.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] In special effects pyrotechnics, lycopodium powder and non-dairy creamer are two common means of producing safe, controlled fire effects.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] To support rapid combustion, the dust must consist of very small particles with a high surface area to volume ratio, thereby making the collective or combined surface area of all the particles very large in comparison to a dust of larger particles.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Dust is defined as powders with particles less than about 500 micrometres in diameter, but finer dust will present a much greater hazard than coarse particles by virtue of the larger total surface area of all the particles.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Below a certain value, the lower explosive limit (LEL), there is insufficient dust to support the combustion at the rate required for an explosion.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] A combustible concentration at or below 25% of the LEL is considered safe.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Similarly, if the fuel to air ratio increases above the upper explosive limit (UEL), there is insufficient oxidant to permit combustion to continue at the necessary rate.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Determining the minimum explosive concentration or maximum explosive concentration of dusts in air is difficult, and consulting different sources can lead to quite different results.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Typical explosive ranges in air are from few dozens grams/m3 for the minimum limit, to few kg/m3 for the maximum limit.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] For example, the LEL for sawdust has been determined to be between 40 and 50 grams/m3.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] It depends on many factors including the type of material used.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Typically, normal atmospheric oxygen can be sufficient to support a dust explosion if the other necessary conditions are also present.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] High-oxygen or pure oxygen environments are considered to be especially hazardous, as are strong oxidizing gases such as chlorine and fluorine.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Also, particulate suspensions of compounds with a high oxidative potential, such as peroxides, chlorates, nitrates, perchlorates, and dichromates, can increase risk of an explosion if combustible materials are also present.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] There are many sources of ignition, and a naked flame need not be the only one: over one half of the dust explosions in Germany in 2005 were from non-flame sources.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] However, it is often difficult to determine the exact source of ignition when investigating after an explosion.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] When a source cannot be found, ignition will often be attributed to static electricity.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Static charges can be generated by external sources, or can be internally generated by friction at the surfaces of particles themselves as they collide or move past one another.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Dust has a very large surface area compared to its mass.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Since burning can only occur at the surface of a solid or liquid, where it can react with oxygen, this causes dust to be much more flammable than bulk materials.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] For example, a 1 kg (2.2 lb) sphere of a combustible material with a density of 1 g/cm3 would be about 12.4 cm (4.9 in) in diameter, and have a surface area of 0.048 m2 (0.52 sq ft).
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] However, if it were broken up into spherical dust particles 50 μm in diametre (about the size of flour particles) it would have a surface area of 120 m2 (1,300 sq ft).
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] This greatly-increased surface area allows the material to burn much faster, and the extremely small mass of each particle allows them to catch on fire with much less energy than the bulk material, as there is no heat loss to conduction within the material.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] When this mixture of fuel and air is ignited, especially in a confined space such as a warehouse or silo, a significant increase in pressure is created, often more than sufficient to demolish the structure.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Even materials that are traditionally thought of as nonflammable (such as aluminium), or slow burning (such as wood), can produce a powerful explosion when finely divided, and can be ignited by even a small spark.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] A dust explosion can cause major damage to structures, equipment, and personnel from violent overpressure or shockwave effects.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Flying objects and debris can cause further damage.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Intense radiant heat from a fireball can ignite the surroundings, or cause severe skin burns in unprotected persons.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] In a tightly enclosed space, the sudden depletion of oxygen can cause asphyxiation.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Where the dust is carbon based (such as in a coal mine), incomplete combustion may cause large amounts of carbon monoxide (the miners' after-damp) to be created.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] This can cause more deaths than the original explosion as well as hindering rescue attempts.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Much research has been carried out in Europe and elsewhere to understand how to control these dangers, but dust explosions still occur.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] The alternatives for making processes and plants safer depend on the industry.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] In the coal mining industry, a methane explosion can initiate a coal dust explosion, which can then engulf an entire mine pit.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] As a precaution, incombustible stone dust may be spread along mine roadways, or stored in trays hanging from the roof, to dilute the coal dust stirred up by a shockwave to the point where it cannot burn.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Mines may also be sprayed with water to inhibit ignition.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Some industries exclude oxygen from dust-raising processes, a precaution known as "inerting".
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Typically this uses nitrogen, carbon dioxide, or argon, which are incombustible gases which can displace oxygen.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] The same method is also used in large storage tanks where flammable vapors can accumulate.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] However, use of oxygen-free gases brings a risk of asphyxiation of the workers.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Workers who need illumination in enclosed spaces where a dust explosion is a high risk often use lamps designed for underwater divers, as they have no risk of producing an open spark due to their sealed waterproof design.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Good housekeeping practices, such as eliminating build-up of combustible dust deposits with a dust collector, also help mitigate the problem.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] Dust clouds are a common source of explosions, causing an estimated 2,000 explosions annually in Europe.
[src:detonation-velocity/dust-explosions] The table lists notable incidents worldwide.
